            <Title>Beat Sheet</Title>
            <Text>This is an adaptation of Blake Snyder’s Beat Sheet for a successful screen play. My thought here isn’t to stick to it precisely (he insists on specific # of pages, with specific things on specific pages) — but to help craft the story in a dramatic, interesting direction.

Re-arrange scenes as needed to align with this pattern.

The length of each beat is expressed as a percentage of the whole, rather than as a precise number of pages. Use this pattern to focus attention on where to tighten things up, where to expand. My rough percentages are out of 110%.  Because we also go the extra mile…. ;-) 

Roughly placing the scenes I’ve outlined so far to see if they can fit this pattern.

I did cards on a white board as well, but then seem to have lost my initial edits based on the card, which then got a bit mixed up. Am reviewing the whole thing to slot the card notes in appropriately. Things to clarify include...

- Who is the main character in a given scene?
- What voice/point-of-view is used in the scene?
- What is the main conflict in the scene?
- What gets resolved within the scene? 
- What is left hanging?

===================================

The cards as identified here are not necessarily in synch with the ones that ended up on the whiteboard, and are represented in the Manuscript outline. Think of the following as a first draft of the beat sheet.

I like the overall flow developed here, but needs more.

