            <Title>Mixry</Title>
            <Text>Mixry
Role in Story
Ramona lives in a sequestration village just outside of Mixry.

The team working to support SPQ goes there to see if she can provide them with information about the Terrapinas, who are rumored to have knowledge of pollination techniques that predated the arrival of Heliops and Riders, and possibly predated the Catastrophe.

It is also a center of intrigue and danger regarding suspected influx of "barbarians" from the north, who Tagabants claim have a Fifth Column in Mixry. Along with all the other things going on, a kind of revolt of the Wesshewen workers spreads from Mixry. This is not actually the same thing, or even directly related to, armed attacks from northern raiders, but Fatunik propaganda portrays it that way, making life even more difficult for the I.W.W. population.
Related Characters


Season


Unique Features
One of the few places in the Saskan Lands where there is a fairly significant population of "foreigners". In this case, folks -- mainly huum -- who came in from the north, the Lands of Wesshewen, seeking sanctuary, safety and/or work in the relatively prosperous and secure borders of the Fatunika.  They mainly do "dirty work" in the fields, ranches and mines (mainly peat-bog) of Norgyte, Salotriza and Givákala and are registered officially as "Internal Wesshewen Workers".   Often underpaid and treated badly, but coming from a land where people are traditionally strong, self-sufficient and free (in the way that pirates are free), the I.W.W's are a constant source of labor strife, going on strike, making demands and so on. 

Description
A desolate watch-tower town on the northern frontier, in the province of Norgyte. Officially managed by the Authority, but rule of law in the town itself is very limited and observance of the duties almost non-existent. 

Full of mercenaries, thieves and con-artists. A few skilled assassins operate from there. 

A haven for mixed- and powered folks in the northeast

Just outside of town are sequestration villages where the Fatunika parks persons deemed a danger to public order and so on, but who have not been condemned for crimes and whose offenses were not serious enough to merit treatments reserved for heretics.  Some of these are run fairly humanely; others less so. 

