        <Document ID="FD23F065-3F0C-406B-AF7D-1606C360810C">
            <Title>Kahilafolk</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="3D8BC1CC-656B-4A1A-8040-FBFA756821F8">
            <Title>Report from Hádika</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="839FA68F-1AD2-4F29-A399-9CEA99F983F8">
            <Title>Time</Title>
            <Text>Related: historical timelines, themes regarding main cultural and language groups.  
See: Structural Elements:Languages  and Structural Elements: Tribes


I liked how Game of Thrones had a pretty detailed perspective on "the seven" god-like figures. Maybe could play with something like that using the 12 standard Jungian archtetypes? ...
Ruler
Creator/artist
Sage
Innocent
Explorer
Rebel
Hero
Wizard
Jester
Everyman
Lover
Caregiver

At one point I'd used elements of Tarot and Qabalah to name the months on some calendars. Maybe these would serve better for names on calendars that have 12 months.


MAJOR CALENDARS

The Agency uses 3 closely-related versions of an astronomical calendar suitable for translation between the other ones.

Fatunik Solar standard for time-keeping and calendaring that is used or at least understood by most actors.  Two versions, the older Juuj and the Reformed Beshquoan

Very similar solar calendars used in The Runes of Bye, the Nye Lands and Mobalbesq. Close to the Fatunik Calendar but with different ways of handling leap-months, leap-years.

Southern/Settan/Sogomsh Lunar calendars.

Many non-astronomical arithmetic calendars used by various sint tribes, cultures, traditions. 

The Terrapin Calendar covers an epoch starting 360,000 years ago. 

The Revolutionary Jacks Calendar cycles through 72 days (three lunar cycles, basically one season) and has little organized sense of years.

Kahila helio-lunar calendar.

Empafarasi/Eelan calendar based on movement of planets, plus solar and lunar.

For the sake of getting started, let's map out the calendars in a spreadsheet, then later adjust for details.

 SOLAR / HELIOPTIC

The original series of months I came up with for the Heliops was derived from the the tarot deck and the Kabbalah/tree of life. Let's make that more unique to the inherent qualities of the story/game.  I don't mind at all mixing/matching from mystical and religious traditions, but don't want a direct steal unless it is for a very particular joke or purposeful reference. 

Here was the original version, with the tarot and Kabbalah references... and some possible alternatives....

Keddar / The Crown		Cheddar
Jokma / The King		The Joker, The Clown
Beana / The Cup
Jexa / Mother of Mercy	(kind of like this one as is)
G'boor / The Book		The Argument
Tifara / The Sword
Netzchad / Victory
Had / The Eternal
Yessad / The Foundation	Azimov
Malkad / The Kingdom
Aelfad / The Fool
Beesad / The Mage

Use a rhyming dictionary to come up with more unique words.
See the Calendar_Calcs spreadsheet. It has much better names for the Fatunik months, etc.

The book Calendrical Algorithms describes all major calendars. Might be better to steal from that, or at least to get some ideas.

UNIVERSAL

The Agency’s understanding of time would be considerably different from inside the Enclosure.  That is where sci-fi / space fiction considerations need to come into play, especially regarding relativity, near-light-speed travel and/or traveling vast distances thru space. 

But don’t get TOO carried away with complex physics; it’s not really the realm of this story and the intention is for the Agency to be not all there any way. The astronomical calendar they use is adapted to the local star system. There is yet another truly "Universal" calendar they use, but that gets us into a different game that I don't intend to represent this time around, involving reincarnation, heavens, hells, time manifolds and so on.

SOLAR vs. LUNAR

The world has two moons. Given the important role that solar vs lunar understanding plays, there are of course both solar calendar (Fatunik, Rider, Outer Lands), lunar calendars that relate to one or both Moons, and helio-lunar (Kahila) ones that try to accomodate both. 

Need to work out the most basic astronomy for this planet, including the seasons/weather patterns for Saskantinon. Make sure the solar and lunar calendars align to it.  What is the length of the actual solar year? Of the lunar revolutions?

May be able to use some software to compute/estimate some of that.


TIDES

There are three main seas involved in the geography of the region, two Great Lakes, one of which is tied to a large salt marsh that connects to the ocean and thus is referred to as a Sea, and several rivers that empty into the seas/ocean.  Some clear sense of tidal events and river flooding patterns will be good to have.

This should also influence the design of some calendars.


MINOR CALENDARS and VARIATIONS

Some of the secret societies, quasi-religious groups, sint communities, as well as particular clans/tribes, may have additional variations, especially with respect to observations of important days and such.


SEASONS, DAYS, WEEKS, HOURS

Day-names, how day-divisions/hours/minutes are named and handled, understanding of leap-years, season, solstices/equinoxes and possibly some stellar events should all be understood for any calendar (which is most of them) that is not 100% arithmetic.

It will also be important to note, for each calendar, when a day begins -- Noon? Midnight? Sunrise? Sunset? Other?  And of course... Noon, etc...  Where?  

How big are the Saskan Lands?  Do folks in the East experience Noon simultaneously with folks in the West?  How much of a time difference is there?  Who decides what time it is in any particular locale?

As far as time-measures under 1 day, this can also vary from place to place, in different provinces, cultures, etc. But we should expect that the Fatunik Standard is the most widespread and commonly used.  Astronomical time can use decimal expressions (some other calendars may do this also) and thus has no need, really, for other kinds of time-keeping.

Some terms I expect to be part of the Fatunik "canon"...

	•	1 wayt = 5 minutes
	•	1 watch = 3 hours = 36 wayts
	•	1 stand = 3 hours = 36 wayts
	•	1 bell = 1.5 hours = 18 wayts

	•	First watch ~~ 3 hours starting at sunset (about 18h - 21h)
	•	Second watch ~~ 3 hours prior to midnight (about 21h - 0h)
	•	Third watch ~~ 3 hours after midnight  (about 0h - 3h)
	•	Fourth watch ~~ 3 hours prior to sunrise (about 3h - 6h)

	•	First stand ~~ 3 hours after sunrise (about 6h - 9h)
	•	Second stand ~~ 3 hours prior to noon (about 9h - 12h)
	•	Third stand ~~ 3 hours after noon (about 12h - 15h)
	•	Fourth stand ~~ 3 hours prior to sunset (about 15h - 18h)




</Text>
